Text.Value: What does forcing them out achieve? They've done nothing.
Don't we? I've studied duergar culture. You have an instinct for survival.
Attack.
You are like the devils. Where they tread, chaos follows.
Stay your hand. This is neither the time nor the place.
I'm nothing like you - I don't kill children.
She made her choice.
'A disease of the flower must not reach the root. Pluck the petals. Sever the branch if you must. But cut out the rot before it infects the whole of the wood.'
A deep elf - in our grove, on this day. A sign. Or rather, a gift.

EditorData.logicalname: React to snake court- Drow / Half Drow

Text.Value: I'll see what can be done about them.
Then I was wise to grant you entry. And you'd be wise to heed my words.
I know the truth. You mean to take the grove for the Shadow Druids.
You'd leave them to die on the road.
So you say. Yet the child walks free.
Is this rite druidic? I have never witnessed such magic.
This rite must be born of powerful magic.
Teachings of the Treefather. Do you agree?
But if your treatment is meant to outlast the rite, you'll be removed with the rest.
A viper bares her fangs defending her brood. I call her mother. You call her monster.
Turning your back on the needy - is this truly the way of Silvanus?
Indeed? But you do exhibit a talent for self-preservation.
That child - what was her crime?
Only a monster would threaten a child.
Indeed? Then above all, you must have a talent for self-preservation.
Away. I have no more need of you.
A shame the grace period ends. The viper's fangs have been bared. She must guard her brood.
Hang on. If we play this right, we might be able to stop this before it starts.
Who better to understand a watchful broodmother than a beloved child of Lolth?
I'd have killed the thief outright.
Is this rite druidic? I have never witnessed such magic.
This rite must be born of powerful magic.
I want you to provide your services to the tiefling leader - Zevlor, he's called. Offer to guide the outlanders out of the grove. I'm sure they'll reward you well.
And still you petitioned on her behalf. Your words are vicious, yet you showed mercy.
Zevlor wants you removed. I'm here to see it done.
I worship Eilistraee - not the Queen of Spiders.
Do you expect pity? You killed a child in cold blood.
Zevlor is dead.
Zevlor's people need refuge. You can't deny them that.
Monsters both, then. Viper to viper.
Who better to understand a watchful broodmother than one who hails from... below?
Indeed? Then when the lightning comes, it has one fewer to strike.
She stole the Idol of Silvanus during prayer, and interrupted the rite.
Teachings of Silvanus, you must agree.
A clear choice, I would say.
You showed great mettle at the gate - the mettle of a skilled sword for hire.
Monsters both, then. Viper to viper. Beast to beast.
You will do more than 'see'.
I don't make a habit of threatening children.
Why are you here? I sent you to Zevlor.

EditorData.logicalname: Quest HasMet - Player sent to zevlor

Text.Value: What?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The rats transform into Druids. This leads to the Denouncing scene.

Text.Value: Why are you here?

EditorData.logicalname: Quest HasMet - Knows Zevlor is dead

Text.Value: Ah - you don't see a monster. You just look at me through one's eyes.
Free from the threat of little children?
Leave.
Go on. Say it. You think I'm a monster.
First you urge grace. Then you speak truth. You've surprised me twice over.
I know your kind from other circles. You see only villains and victims.

EditorData.logicalname: Sagha knows you are a druid

Text.Value: Think it through. Anger Kagha, and the whole grove could suffer.
Please - we have nothing in common.
So you say. Yet you share their infernal blood.
You've the skin of a beast. If only your heart was so bold.
Speak, while there's time.
What does forcing them out achieve? They've done nothing.
I came on Zevlor's behalf. His people could perish if you force them out.
Nothing? They've done everything.
Turning your back on the needy - is this truly the way of Silvanus?
The viper can stand down. Zevlor is already dead.
Do what you want. It's none of my concern.
You will do more than speak.
A grey dwarf - in our grove, on this day. A sign. Or rather, a gift.
This tale ends but one way: with the outlander rot cleansed and the grove forever shrouded.
Reach for your weapon.
I am First Druid now. I protect the circle, whatever the cost.
The outlander serves Zevlor! Circle - to arms. Let no parasite live!
Now the Idol of Silvanus is returned and the rite has resumed. We will seal the grove. Free from harm. Free of intruders.
The Rite of Thorns. It is the Treefather's gift, that none come to harm. When we speak the final prayer, the Great Vine will sprout forth.
The devilspawn imperilled my brood. I bared my fangs to defend it. Choice. Consequence.
The others might consider this sacrilege. But we know the truth: it is necessity.
Why, I don't know or care.
Ah yes. You like to meddle. See what happens. So let me tell you what happens next.

EditorData.logicalname: Child dead, gave evil answer earlier

Text.Value: You are like all the rest. Where devils tread, chaos follows.
Yes - you would say so. I know your kind. You see only villains and victims.
First you urge grace. Then you speak truth. To think a devil could surprise me twice over.
You must let them stay. They've done nothing to harm you.
None of this can happen while outlanders infect us. Silvanus demands that we choke them out.
The Rite of Thorns is risky magic. Is it not banned in your circle?
Stand down.
I know your kind. You see only victims and villains.
Accidents do not exist. There is only choice and consequence.
I took back the Idol of Silvanus and the rite has resumed. We will seal the grove. Free from harm. Free of intruders.
Your iron will is impressive - if a touch inflexible.
Words you have twisted to justify your cruelty.
You will offer your services to the tieflings' leader - Zevlor, he's called. And you will guide the outlanders out of the grove.
Prattle all you want. The refugees aren't my concern.
I hardly know every line of doctrine.
Then it seems I'd best speak to Zevlor.
A viper bares her fangs defending her brood. Is it not her nature to strike at invaders?
Then they soon know the sting of my venom.
Then you know I heed his wisdom. I protect the circle, whatever the cost.
Zevlor believes his people will perish on the road.
I know the Treefather's teachings as well as you.
Zevlor sent me. His people won't survive out there.
You cast out the guiltless. You shame your order.
You speak in paradox. I care not for steel, but I know if it bends - it breaks. I will not allow this grove to be broken.
Bah. I'd thought one like you might understand. When a threat makes itself known, you remove it.
Attack.
So you say. Yet you share their infernal blood. And the child walks free.
Yes?
*Past teachings come into focus. The Rite of Thorns is a rare practice, outlawed in most circles for causing more harm than it eases.*
A viper bares her fangs defending her brood. Is it not her nature to strike at invaders?
Have you finished your chatter? Then you will give me your ear.
You can't just force these people out.
Don't we? I've studied drow culture. You have a talent for self-preservation.
...the viper must strike.
Indeed? Then removing his people should provide you little challenge.
I have no love for the Queen of Spiders.
And if it is? Strangers are the scourge; the rite is the remedy. No laws can change that.
Monster? Too kind. A demon, more like.
I want you to provide your services to Zevlor. Offer to guide the outlanders out of the grove. I'm sure they'll reward you well.
Not at all. That was quite a show.
First, you stay silent. Then, you speak truth. To think an outsider could surprise me twice over.
You're protecting your own - sometimes cruelty is required.
You protected your own without hesitation - my compliments.
I've done enough. They're your problem, not mine.
And yet you petitioned on the thief's behalf. A curious display of mercy.
Hold. Give diplomacy a chance to do its job.
They're to be gone before final prayer. If they are not...
Then we agree. Preservation is not luxury, it is not zealotry. It is necessity.
Finally. Let's have some fun.

EditorData.NodeContext: You've been bored, now you're ready to rip someone's throat out.

Text.Value: Words I heed to the letter to keep my brood safe.
Yes. Yes. This could be the true way of Silvanus.
And mine perish if he stays.
They may die on the road.
That depends. It was an accident - wasn't it?
You will offer your services to Zevlor, guide the outlanders out of the grove.
The grove will be cloaked in bramble and thorn. No one enters, no one leaves. Sanctuary.
Get out. We have no more business.
Nettie, yes. She's bumbling about somewhere.
Honestly, I just wanted to see what would happen.
The viper bares her fangs defending her brood. It is only right that she strike the killing blow.
They will die if they stay.
You showed great mettle at the gate - the mettle of a skilled sword for hire.
Keep talking. Nothing to be gained in picking a fight with a fanatic.
I'm told there is a healer here. Where is she?
No matter. I took back the Idol of Silvanus and the rite has resumed. We will seal the grove. Free from harm. Free of intruders.
I do hope you didn't come expecting my thanks. That would be most perplexing.
Then why do you doubt my acts and intent?
Zevlor is dead.

Synopsis: Player speaks with Kagha, the secret Shadow druid. Various paths of conversation reflect whether Kagha's actions led to a child's death or not. She may be neutral/Machiavellian or pure evil, depending.
